Date: Tue, 30 Apr 2002
From: Jaime R. Torres, ProMED-ESP
Source: Athens News Agency, 30 Apr 2002 [edited
<http://www.ana.gr/>


Killer myocarditis virus identified as strain of Coxsackie B
-------------------------------------------------------
Scientists from the First Microbiology Laboratory of the University
of Thessalonica announced on Mon 28 Apr 2002 that the virus
responsible for the 3 cases of fatal acute myocarditis and dozens of
cases of cardiac complications reported in Greece over the past few
weeks has been isolated and identified.

The implicated virus is the enterovirus Coxsackie B. The report from
the laboratory [stated that the identification had been made through
molecular virology techniques [presumably PCR - Mod.LM applied to
samples of cardiac muscle from the 3 fatal cases, as well as from
patients with symptoms of acute myocarditis who had survived.

